#include <cstdio>

struct Node {
    int value;
    Node *next;
};

/* Free every node in the list. */
static void destroy_list(Node *head) {
    /* Walk from the head to the tail, deleting each node as we go.
     * Called when the owning container is destroyed. */
    for (Node *cur = head; cur != nullptr; cur = cur->next) {
        delete cur;
    }
}

int main() {
    Node *c = new Node{3, nullptr};
    Node *b = new Node{2, c};
    Node *a = new Node{1, b};
    destroy_list(a);
    std::printf("done\n");
    return 0;
}

messages.content:
THOUGHT: The AddressSanitizer report clearly indicates a heap-use-after-free error. The crash occurs in `destroy_list` when trying to access `cur->next` after `cur` has already been deleted. The loop logic is flawed: it deletes the current node (`delete cur`) and then attempts to advance to `cur->next`, but `cur` is no longer valid after deletion. This causes a use-after-free when accessing `cur->next` in the next iteration. The root cause is a classic double-free or use-after-free due to incorrect pointer management in the loop.

ROOT CAUSE: In `destroy_list`, the loop deletes the current node (`delete cur`) and then attempts to access `cur->next` in the next iteration. After `delete cur`, the memory is freed, so accessing `cur->next` is undefined behavior. The loop condition `cur = cur->next` dereferences a dangling pointer, triggering the heap-use-after-free error.

LOCAL FIX: Modify the loop to save the next pointer before deleting the current node. This ensures the traversal continues safely.

```cpp
static void destroy_list(Node *head) {
    while (head != nullptr) {
        Node *next = head->next;
        delete head;
        head = next;
    }
}
```

GLOBAL FIX: Replace raw pointers with a smart pointer (e.g., `std::unique_ptr`) to manage ownership and prevent manual memory management errors. This eliminates the risk of use-after-free and double-free by enforcing RAII semantics.

```cpp
struct Node {
    int value;
    std::unique_ptr<Node> next;
};
```

With this change, `destroy_list` becomes trivial and safe:

```cpp
static void destroy_list(std::unique_ptr<Node> head) {
    // No explicit deletion needed — RAII handles it.
}
```

This structural change prevents the entire class of memory management bugs by removing manual `new`/`delete` and enforcing ownership semantics at compile time.

